Greetings from Italy.
36 posts
Skoop
Ars Legatus Legionis
et Subscriptor
Tribus: Valle d'Itria, Italia
Registered: Aug 12, 2000Posts: 21356
Posted: Wed Nov 30, 2011 10:47 am
After writing here for several years about doing it, we did it. The Skoops now live in southern Italy, in the Puglia Region, the heel of the boot-shaped country. We've taken a three-level apartment house in a small city founded in about 1260 and built to its current architecture in the baroque style in the 17th and 18th centuries. We live about 100 paces from the Basilica of St. Martin, the baroque masterpiece that dominates the main piazza.After selling our house stateside and liquidating most of our stuff, we traveled with 4 large suitcases that just met airline size and weight codes, and two carry-ons. Got a 10-down DSL line turned on in the house several days ago and I'm writing from the mini-ITX box that I built for the very purpose of traveling small and light. We're having a great time. The neighbors and townspeople have been warm and welcoming. Even the gov't officials with whom we've had to deal have been helpful and accommodating. Mrs. Skoop is a dual citizen through her Italian grandfather who emigrated to New York about 100 years ago. Our impressions, not only here but elsewhere in Italy, is that Italo-Americans are thought of with regard in this country. The Mrs.' EU/Italy passport is greasing a lot of skids in the paperwork dept. I have an appointment to get my "green card" application going in a couple of weeks. So far, everything has gone swimmingly. Even the officer with the Commissariat of the State Police we had to see get my appt. welcomed us to town. Eating well, the air is good, it's clear and bright, the wine is stellar. Retirement to the dolce vita. And now, the pics. Our street and the house, some of the town during sunlight and the surrounding valley, some of the Wednesday market, nighttime views, and some of St. Martin inside. Vlip
