NYCEsquire wrote:My family is from Puglia (Triggiano, Bari actually). I often think about retiring to Italy, or even a quiet beach somewhere. But... won't you get bored of the slow, low-tech life? That's what really stops my daydreaming in its tracks.Retirement. UR doing it wrong.In Italy anyway, the smaller the town the slower, low-techage will be the life. If you're often thinking about retiring to Italy, but you're concerned about being bored, then what is it that you want out of retirement? Go live in Florence or Milan or Rome or Bologna. Then, you can still be in New York, only there will be more Italian speakers than where you live now. But you can speak English there and no one will bat an eye.I'm here in a small city (40K) to eat and live well; travel the Mediterranean, Balkans, the Continent, and North Africa; learn more of another language; go to cooking school in Lecce; hike in the Dolomites; sit in the sun; drink good wine; and surf Ars Technica. Among other pursuits, and being bored is not one of them. I was just in Triggiano last week. Went to a supermarket there on our way back from Ikea.
