Posted: Mon Dec 05, 2011 9:26 am
yd wrote:How much do you figure one of those nice looking apartments with balconies overlooking the piaza(s) might go for Skoop?Rule of thumb for a bare minimum purchase: 2000Euros/sq. meter in the historic center. Choice views, historical or political significance, family connections will add to the cost, perhaps significantly. IF you could get an owner to sell. There's a lot of property for sale in Italy because family sizes are small and the kids want to get out of lesser populated areas because there's no fun (for them) and not much work. But choice properties and those of the gentry will almost never go on the market.
Skoop
Ars Legatus Legionis
et Subscriptor
Tribus: Valle d'Itria, Italia
Registered: Aug 12, 2000Posts: 21356
Posted: Mon Dec 05, 2011 9:31 am
Quote:I could swear you were talking about buying something in the country.Perhaps in future. Right now we want to get more integrated and improve our language and social skills. Doing that is much more difficult being isolated out in the countryside. Plus, we don't want a car. We can find whatever we want close in, and the train station is a ten minute walk. Bari, large city on the coast to the NE is an hour and 20 minutes on the train. Bonus: Ikea Bari is on the train line. Much of our household goods came from there. Our kitchen will be installed by them in a few weeks.
Skoop
Ars Legatus Legionis
et Subscriptor
Tribus: Valle d'Itria, Italia
Registered: Aug 12, 2000Posts: 21356
Posted: Mon Dec 05, 2011 9:43 am
Happysin wrote:I'd love to hear the details of you formalizing your immigration. Italy has been one of the places I have seriously considered moving to later in life. I loved it when I was there, and adore going back (though I'm way overdue).Also, have you taken immersion courses in Italian? Were you already comfortable with the language? Acclimating as a resident seems like it would be a lot different than going even as a long-stay tourist.I applied for Italian citizenship a few months ago before we left. I can do so as the spouse of an Italian citizen. Had to provide my birth and citizenship docs, and letters with apostilles from the states I lived in since 14 which stated that I didn't have a criminal record. Process takes about two years. In the meantime, I have a multiple-entry family visa that is good for a year, that I got from the San Francisco Consulate, which services Oregon where I last lived stateside. Next week, I go to the provincial capital (Taranto) office of the state police to apply for my green card. With that, I am legal to stay in the country and my visa can expire without issue. Eventually, my citizenship should come through and obviate the green card. Re: language, both of us listened to the Pimsleur language course in Italian over and over for several years, and from that got a pretty good basic handle on ordinary daily dialogue, syntax, and verb forms. We also read a lot of Italian language teaching texts. With all of the latinate words that have been incorporated into English, it's really not that difficult to guess at a word, particularly verbs, if it's not clear. Plus, we're both two-time returned Peace Corps Volunteers with a lot of language experience, so we kind of have the knack. Italian is a hell of lot easier to pick up than Thai, Lao, Nepali, or Tharu. 36 posts
